The curriculum is made up of six subject groups and a core. Students take courses from each subject group, except for the arts and the elective group, where they may choose to focus on either one or two subjects.
The IB diploma programme requires students to:

- study six subjects, including two modern languages;

-study a broad range of subjects rather than just a few subjects narrowly defined;

-complete two-year, in-depth study in each subject;

- write an extended essay on a topic of your choice;

-take part in a programme called CAS (Creativity, Action, Service), which focuses on extracurricular activities;

-complete a theory of knowledge course, which helps them reflect on their learning;

- learn a second language;

- complete a research project.

The IB Diploma is not a qualification but a programme. It is awarded to students who have completed all of the above requirements successfully. Because there are no final examinations for the IB Diploma, and because it takes into account students' performance throughout the two-year programme, it is considered more balanced and holistic than other qualifications. It also allows for more flexibility and creativity in subject choices. For example, students can choose a second science or second mathematics course in addition to the first, or they can choose a second language instead. This means that students can really tailor the IB Diploma to meet their own needs and interests, while still completing the full programme. However, students must complete all six subjects.

                        What is the IB mission statement?

The International Baccalaureate aims to develop inquiring, knowledgeable and caring young people who help to create a better and more peaceful world through intercultural understanding and respect. To this end, the organization works with schools, governments and international organizations to develop challenging programmes of international education and rigorous assessment. These programmes encourage students across the world to become active, compassionate and lifelong learners who understand that other people, with their differences, can also be right. -


